article.description:
Cheryl Ford and Barbara Farris each
scored 15 points to help the Detroit Shock clinch the East's third
seed in the playoffs with a 68-54 win over the Charlotte Sting on
Sunday.
article.headline: Detroit clinched the third seed in the East
article.linkText: Shock clinches playoff spot with victory
article.story:
Auburn Hills, Mich. (AP) -- The Detroit Shock got the victory
they needed for a chance to defend their WNBA championship.

Cheryl Ford and Barbara Farris each scored 15 points to help the
Shock clinch the East's third seed in the playoffs with a 68-54 win
over the Charlotte Sting on Sunday.

"I don't really care who we play, " Shock coach Bill Laimbeer
said. "Because we are going to win the Eastern Conference."

Merlakia Jones finished with 12 points for the Shock.

Allison Feaster led the Sting with 12 points. Tammy Sutton-Brown
and Charlotte Smith-Taylor each added 11 for Charlotte.

The Shock led 27-23 at the break despite hitting only five of
their first 21 shots. A 19-7 run helped Detroit take the lead at
the half. Deanna Nolan made two free throws with 1:18 remaining in
the period to give the Shock their first lead.

"(Charlotte) came out of the blocks just fine, but we knew at
that point, it was still early," Detroit center Ruth Riley said.
"But in this league, we know we're going to be able to make plays
like we did. You just have to remain confident in your game plan."

Detroit continued its torrid shooting in the second half, and
Riley hit a jumper from the top of the key to give the Shock their
biggest lead at 33-23.

Charlotte closed within three points midway through the second
half and was within two points with 6:25 remaining when
Sutton-Brown scored inside. But Detroit took control down the
stretch and pushed its lead to double figures.

Detroit's second-half surge was paced by Ford, who scored 14 of
her 15 points after halftime.

"I knew my teammates were depending on me," Ford said. "So I
knew I just had to come in and hit some shots."

With a spot in the playoffs secured, Detroit knows it must play
with confidence if it hopes to defend its title.

"I think we'll be OK," Ford said. "We know how hard we have
to play and that at this point, anything can happen. So I think our
mind is set right."
